<TITLE> Google executives jailed in Italy </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ITALY, Feb 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters)-- Three men are sentenced to six months in prison after being found guilty of invading the privacy of a boy with Down's Syndrome. The judge in this Milan court reads out his verdict in a privacy violation case. At the centre of it - three executives from the Internet search engine giant, Google. The case was brought by the father of a boy with Down's Syndrome, who was the subject of a video posted via Google in September 2006. Three men have been given jail terms. A fourth has been acquitted. Bill Echikson, Google senior communications manager, says, "We are going to appeal this decision because we believe that it poses a crucial question for the freedom on which the Internet is built. None of these three employees had anything to do with this video, they didn't upload it, they didn't film it, they didn't review it and yet they have been found guilty. And so if this is left to stand we believe that it would threaten the very freedom that the Internet has brought about." Lawyers for Google said that the video - which showed four high school students in Turin, tormenting the boy - was removed as soon as they heard about it. Prosecutors, however, accused Google of negligence and said the video remained online for two months even though some users had asked for it to be taken d
